 following consonant is articulated at the velum, like /g/. In general, /n/ is the underlying form and /ɱ/, /n̺/, and /ŋ/ are all allophones of that phoneme.%0a%3c %0a%3c In assimilation of place of articulation, the mouth configures itself to achieve the place of articulation of the following consonant preemptively, but the tongue or lips fully block air from coming out of the mouth so that it comes out of the nose, making the nasal sound. Then, to articulate the following consonant, the mouth does not move because it is already in the correct place of articulation for the consonant. %0a%3c 	%0a%3c English exhibits a similar pattern as well, as we saw in class with the example ‘in France’ where the /n/ in ‘in’ becomes /ɱ/, just like in Spanish. The same goes for /n/ becoming /ŋ/ before velar consonants, like in the word ‘engulf’ ([ɨŋgʌlf]).%0a%3c %0a%3c Source: https://www.staff.ncl.ac.uk/i.e.mackenzie/neutralir.htm %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
